The isoelectric point of Bicine is simply the average of the two pK\(_a\)s.

\text{pI} = \frac{\text{pK}_{a_1} + \text{pK}_{a_2}}{2}

\text{pI} = \frac{2.3 + 8.3}{2} = 5.3

At this pH the carboxyl group is mainly unprotonated whereas the tertiary nitrogen is nearly fully protonated and thus the average charge is zero. Using the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation we can calculate the ratio of protonated to unprotonated species for each group. For the carboxyl group:

\text{pH} = \text{pK}_{\text{COOH}} + \log \frac{[\text{COO}^-]}{[\text{COOH}]}

\left[\frac{\text{COO}^-}{\text{COOH}}\right] = 10^{(\text{pH} - \text{pK}_{\text{COOH}})} = 10^{(5.3-2.3)}

\left[\frac{\text{COO}^-}{\text{COOH}}\right] = 10^{3} = 1000

This calculation shows that at pH 7.5 only approximately 0.1% is protonated. The calculation for the tertiary nitrogen of bicine is as follows:

\text{pH} = \text{pK}_{a} + \log \frac{[\text{N}]}{[\text{NH}^+]}

\left[\frac{\text{N}}{\text{NH}^+}\right] = 10^{(\text{pH} - \text{pK}_{a})} = 10^{(5.3-8.3)}

\left[\frac{\text{N}}{\text{NH}^+}\right] = 10^{-3} = 0.001

We should have anticipated this result, namely the ratios are inverse, because we are starting at a pH that is equidistant from each pK\(_a\).

To adjust the pH from 5.3 to 7.5 will require addition of NaOH. The exact amount is determined by application of the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation to both groups to determine the ratio of protonated to unprotonated forms of both species. For the carboxyl group:

\text{pH} = \text{pK}_{\text{COOH}} + \log \frac{[\text{COO}^-]}{[\text{COOH}]}

\left[\frac{\text{COO}^-}{\text{COOH}}\right] = 10^{(\text{pH} - \text{pK}_{\text{COOH}})} = 10^{(7.5-2.3)}

\left[\frac{\text{COO}^-}{\text{COOH}}\right] = 10^{5.2} = 1.58 \times 10^{5}

For the amino group:

\text{pH} = \text{pK}_\text{a} + \log \left(\frac{[\text{N}]}{[\text{NH}^+]} \right)

\left[\frac{[\text{N}]}{[\text{NH}^+]}\right] = 10^{(\text{pH}-\text{pK}_\text{a})} = 10^{(7.5-8.3)}

\left[\frac{[\text{N}]}{[\text{NH}^+]}\right] = 10^{-0.8} = 0.158

